{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/592"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.04,0.04,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"469"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department via ambulance, unconscious, following a head-on motor vehicle accident. He was the sole occupant of a vehicle traveling at 40 km/h. He is resuscitated. A CT head is performed, which shows an intracranial haemorrhage. He has a medical history of a prosthetic heart valve for which he takes warfarin. His INR is 2.5 (0.9-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to stopping warfarin, which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his anticoagulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitamin K and Beriplex","Beriplex, fresh frozen plasma, red cell transfusion","Fresh frozen plasma, red cell transfusion, cryoprecipitate","Red cell transfusion, cryoprecipitate, vitamin K","Cryoprecipitate, vitamin K, Beriplex"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a life-threatening intracranial haemorrhage while on warfarin therapy. In such cases of clinically significant bleeding where warfarin-induced coagulopathy is a contributing factor, the effect of warfarin should be actively and rapidly reversed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin K and Beriplex\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate combination for managing this patient\u0027s anticoagulation. Intravenous vitamin K is given to promote the synthesis of vitamin K-dependent clotting factors. Beriplex is a 4-factor prothrombin complex concentrate, containing all vitamin K-dependent clotting factors and rapidly reverses warfarin\u0027s effect by providing factors II, VII, IX, and X. Fresh frozen plasma is not given with Beriplex because Beriplex contains an adequate concentration of coagulation factor VII. Beriplex has now replaced Prothrombinex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeriplex, fresh frozen plasma, and red cell transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not the optimal choice. Whilst Beriplex is appropriate, FFP and red cell transfusion are not routinely indicated for warfarin reversal. Red cells are used to replace lost blood volume and improve oxygen-carrying capacity but do not directly address the coagulation problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh frozen plasma, red cell transfusion, and cryoprecipitate\u003C/strong\u003E is suboptimal. While FFP can help reverse warfarin\u0027s effects, it is less effective and takes longer to administer than Beriplex. Cryoprecipitate, which contains fibrinogen, factor VIII, factor XIII, and von Willebrand factor, is not specifically indicated for warfarin reversal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell transfusion, cryoprecipitate, and vitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for rapid warfarin reversal. While vitamin K is appropriate, red cells and cryoprecipitate do not directly address the warfarin-induced coagulopathy. This combination lacks a rapid method of replacing vitamin K-dependent factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryoprecipitate, vitamin K, and Beriplex\u003C/strong\u003E is not the ideal combination. Although vitamin K and Beriplexare appropriate, cryoprecipitate is not specifically indicated for warfarin reversal. In this scenario, FFP would be more beneficial than cryoprecipitate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the management of warfarin-associated life-threatening bleeding requires a multi-faceted approach. Vitamin K promotes new factor synthesis and Beriplex provides immediate factor replacement. This combination ensures rapid and effective reversal of warfarin\u0027s anticoagulant effect, which is crucial in managing this patient\u0027s intracranial haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IV vitamin K given and Beriplex is used in clinically significant bleeding associated with warfarin","Fresh frozen plasma is added in cases of life-threatening bleeding associated with warfarin","Different blood products have specific indications in managing coagulopathies and bleeding"],"references":["Australian Red Cross. Guidelines for the Management of Elevated INR in Adults [internet]; 2017 [updated 2017 Feb 23 cited 2021 Feb 09]. Available from: https://transfusion.com.au/disease_therapeutics/warfarin/guidelines_warfarin_reversal","Milling TJ, Voronov A, Schmidt DS, et al. Long-Term Safety of a Four-Factor Prothrombin Complex Concentrate (Kcentra\u00ae/Beriplex\u00ae P/N): An Updated Pharmacovigilance Review. Thromb Haemost 2025;125:46\u201357."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"592"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T16:56:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T16:56:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d